# Adding Transparency to a CSS Element

There are several ways to add transparency to an element with background color `#287891`:

## 1. Using RGBA Color
The most flexible approach - allows you to keep the element's content fully opaque while making the background semi-transparent:

```css
.element {
    background-color: rgba(40, 120, 145, 0.7); /* 0.7 is 70% opacity */
}
```

You can adjust the last value (alpha channel) from 0 (fully transparent) to 1 (fully opaque).

## 2. Using HEX with Alpha
A newer method that adds two digits for transparency to a hex color:

```css
.element {
    background-color: #28789180; /* 80 is about 50% opacity in hex */
}
```

## 3. Using Opacity Property
This makes the entire element transparent (including content and borders):

```css
.element {
    background-color: #287891;
    opacity: 0.7; /* 70% opacity */
}
```

## Examples with Different Transparency Levels

For your color `#287891`:

```css
/* Slightly transparent (90%) */
background-color: rgba(40, 120, 145, 0.9);

/* Moderately transparent (70%) */
background-color: rgba(40, 120, 145, 0.7);

/* Very transparent (30%) */
background-color: rgba(40, 120, 145, 0.3);
```

The RGBA method is usually preferred since it only affects the background color while leaving text and other content fully visible.
Why does this element move further up when toggled? 
```css components/Toggle/Toggle.css
:root {
    --primary-color: #287891;
    --secondary-color: #ffffff;
    --tertiary-color: transparent;
    --font-size-compact: 12px;
    --font-size-default: 1.25rem;
