# Why the Toggle Element Moves Up When Toggled

The toggle element is moving up when toggled because of a border being added only in the checked state, which changes the overall dimensions of the element.

## The Issue

In this line of your CSS:

```css
.toggle-checkbox:checked + .toggle-label {
    background-color: #28789170;
    border: 1px solid transparent;
}
```

You're adding a `1px solid transparent` border **only when the toggle is checked**. This causes the element to grow by 1px on all sides when toggled on, which changes its position.

## Solutions

### Option 1: Always Include the Border
Add the same border to the unchecked state so dimensions remain consistent:

```css
.toggle-label {
    /* existing properties */
    border: 1px solid transparent;
}
```

### Option 2: Use Box-Sizing
Use `box-sizing: border-box` to include borders in the element's dimensions:

```css
.toggle-label {
    box-sizing: border-box;
    /* other properties */
}
```

### Option 3: Remove the Border
If the transparent border isn't visually necessary:

```css
.toggle-checkbox:checked + .toggle-label {
    background-color: #28789170;
    /* remove the border: 1px solid transparent; line */
}
```

### Option 4: Compensate with Positioning
Adjust the position to counteract the border's effect:

```css
.toggle-checkbox:checked + .toggle-label {
    background-color: #28789170;
    border: 1px solid transparent;
    margin: -1px;  /* Compensate for the border */
}
```

The first two options are generally preferred as they maintain layout consistency regardless of the toggle state.
