# Adding Background Color to Unchecked Toggle

To add a background color to the toggle when it's unchecked, you should modify the `.toggle-label` selector, as this controls the appearance of the background "track" of the toggle.

## Solution

Add or modify the background-color property in the `.toggle-label` selector:

```css
.toggle-label {
    position: absolute;
    cursor: pointer;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    bottom: 0;
    background-color: #e0e0e0; /* Add your desired unchecked color here */
    transition: 0.4s;
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    border: 1px solid transparent; /* Add this to maintain consistent dimensions */
}
```

## Explanation

- You already have a style for the checked state (`.toggle-checkbox:checked + .toggle-label`), so the `.toggle-label` style sets the default appearance.
- Consider replacing `#e0e0e0` with your preferred color or using a CSS variable for consistency.
- I included the `border: 1px solid transparent` to solve the shifting issue we identified earlier.

## Alternative - Using CSS Variables

For better maintainability, you could use CSS variables:

```css
:root {
    /* your existing variables */
    --toggle-unchecked-color: #e0e0e0;
    --toggle-checked-color: #28789170;
}

.toggle-label {
    /* other properties */
    background-color: var(--toggle-unchecked-color);
    border: 1px solid transparent;
}

.toggle-checkbox:checked + .toggle-label {
    background-color: var(--toggle-checked-color);
}
```

This approach keeps your color scheme consistent and makes it easier to update in the future.
